{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536939"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:11:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15843"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.62,0.1,0.06,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103162"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85607"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5780"},{"type":"tags","id":"5812"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36022"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44430"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103162"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of low back pain. Over the past three days, he has developed a mild fever and reports that his back pain is worse than usual. The pain is worse in the morning, improves with activity, and returns after prolonged standing or walking. He denies any radiation of pain to the legs or changes in bowel or bladder function. He has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis of both knees, and rheumatoid arthritis for which he takes amlodipine, paracetamol, and methotrexate. He is a retired builder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits except a temperature of 37.9\u00b0C. There is reduced range of movement in all directions of the lumbar spine with associated paravertebral muscle tenderness. Straight leg raise is negative bilaterally. Lower limb power, sensation, and reflexes are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to establish the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nuclear medicine bone scan","Magnetic resonance imaging","Blood cultures","Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry scan","Plain radiographs"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a chronic history of mechanical back pain, but the recent onset of fever and worsening pain in the context of immunosuppressive therapy are red flag symptoms. These features raise concern for possible spinal infection (such as vertebral osteomyelitis or discitis) or malignancy, both of which require prompt investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation in this context. MRI is highly sensitive for detecting spinal infection, malignancy, and epidural abscess, and provides detailed information about soft tissues, discs, and neural structures. The presence of immunosuppression and fever makes it essential to exclude serious underlying pathology. Computed tomography (CT) scan provides excellent bony detail and may show erosive changes in vertebral endplates in cases of infection. However, CT is less sensitive than MRI for early infection or malignancy, particularly for assessing soft tissue involvement, epidural extension, or spinal cord compression. CT may be used if MRI is contraindicated (e.g., in patients with certain metallic implants or severe claustrophobia) or unavailable, but MRI remains the gold standard for evaluating suspected spinal infection or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are important in the workup of suspected spinal infection and would likely be ordered alongside imaging. However, they alone cannot confirm the diagnosis of spinal infection or determine its location and extent. Blood cultures may be negative in a significant proportion of vertebral osteomyelitis cases, making them insufficient as a standalone investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear medicine bone scan\u003C/strong\u003E can detect increased bone turnover and may be positive in infection or malignancy, but lacks specificity and anatomical detail. It is generally reserved for cases where MRI is not available or inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual-energy X-ray absorptiometry scan\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess bone mineral density and diagnose osteoporosis. It does not provide information about infection, malignancy, or acute changes in the spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain radiographs\u003C/strong\u003E are useful for detecting fractures, gross bony abnormalities, or advanced degenerative changes, but are insensitive for early infection or malignancy and would not be sufficient to exclude serious pathology in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed flag symptoms in back pain that warrant urgent imaging include: recent onset of fever, immunosuppression, unexplained weight loss, history of malignancy, recent trauma, age over 50 years with new pain, night pain, neurological deficits, and changes in bowel or bladder function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Red flag symptoms such as recent fever and immunosuppression warrant urgent imaging in chronic back pain.","Magnetic resonance imaging is the investigation of choice to assess for infection or malignancy in the spine.","Chronic mechanical back pain without red flags is usually managed conservatively, but new concerning features require prompt evaluation."],"references":["Chou R, Qaseem A, Snow V, Casey D, Cross JT Jr, Shekelle P et al. Diagnosis and treatment of low back pain: a joint clinical practice guideline from the American College of Physicians and the American Pain Society. Ann Intern Med. 2007 Oct 2;147(7):478-91. Available at: https://www.acpjournals.org/doi/10.7326/0003-4819-147-7-200710020-00006","Downie A, Williams CM, Henschke N, Hancock MJ, Ostelo RW, de Vet HC, Maher CG. Red flags to screen for malignancy in patients with low-back pain. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2013 Feb 28;2013(2):CD008686. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1002/14651858.CD008686.pub2","Jenkins HJ, Hancock MJ, French SD, Maher CG, Magnussen JS. Rates and predictors of lumbar spine imaging in patients presenting with low back pain in Australian primary care: a cohort study. Med J Aust. 2021 Mar 1;214(4):181-187. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2021/214/4/rates-and-predictors-lumbar-spine-imaging-patients-presenting-low-back-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85607"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85607"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T13:05:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T13:06:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103162"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"